The need for social approval and the assumption that the group's beliefs and practices are right are two reasons why individuals conform. Regardless of knowledge uncertainty, the demand for social acceptability exists. Group size, unanimity, and the presence of a confident leader or authority figure are three characteristics that impact compliance. The presence of a confident leader or authority figure refers to the perceived expertise or status of the person leading the group. Group size refers to the number of people in the group, unanimity refers to the level of agreement among group members, and the presence of a confident leader or authority figure refers to the perceived expertise or status of the person leading the group. 